{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476207"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:42:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:42:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13700"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13700"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.11,0.68,0.02,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6316"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51426"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6316"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13700"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36710"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2018"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16549"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51426"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of facial puffiness and dark-coloured urine. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His parents report that he had a sore throat about three weeks ago, which resolved without treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is periorbital oedema and mild pitting oedema of the lower limbs. Urinalysis reveals haematuria and proteinuria. Blood tests show elevated serum creatinine of 120 \u03bcmol/L (45-90) and urea of 10 mmol/L (2.5-6.5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the next best investigation to assist with diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum complement levels","Renal biopsy","Antistreptolysin O titre","Urine culture","Throat swab for streptococcal antigen"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is highly suggestive of post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis. The patient has a history of a recent sore throat, followed by the classic triad of oedema, hypertension, and abnormal urinalysis (haematuria and proteinuria) about three weeks later. These features, along with the elevated creatinine and urea, strongly support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eantistreptolysin O titre (ASOT)\u003C/strong\u003E is the next best investigation to assist with confirming the diagnosis. ASOT is used to detect recent streptococcal infections, which are the most common cause of post-infectious glomerulonephritis in children. ASOT levels typically rise 1-2 weeks after the initial infection and remain elevated for several months, making it an ideal test in this scenario where the throat infection occurred three weeks prior.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum complement levels\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly C3, are often low in acute post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis. However, while supportive of the diagnosis, they are not specific for confirming a recent streptococcal infection. C3 levels typically normalise within 6-8 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure and is not routinely required to diagnose post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis when the clinical presentation is typical, as in this case. It may be considered in atypical presentations or when the diagnosis is uncertain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eurine culture\u003C/strong\u003E would not be helpful in confirming a recent streptococcal throat infection. It is more relevant for diagnosing urinary tract infections, which is not the likely diagnosis given the clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethroat swab for streptococcal antigen\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be positive at this stage, as the throat infection occurred three weeks ago. Streptococcal antigens are typically only detectable during the acute phase of the infection or shortly thereafter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while all these investigations may have a role in the workup of glomerulonephritis, the ASOT is the most appropriate next step to confirm the suspected diagnosis of post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis in this clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antistreptolysin O titre (ASOT) is used to confirm a recent streptococcal infection in the context of post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis.","Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis typically presents 1-3 weeks after a streptococcal throat infection with oedema, hypertension, and abnormal urinalysis."],"references":["CDC, Post Streptococcal Glomerulonephritis: https://www.cdc.gov/groupastrep/diseases-public/post-streptococcal.htmlAbout Post Streptococcal Glomerulonephritis. In: CDC [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.cdc.gov/group-a-strep/about/post-streptococcal-glomerulonephritis.html","Brant Pinheiro SV, de Freitas VB, de Castro GV, Rufino Madeiro BC, de Ara\u00fajo SA, Silva Ribeiro TF. Acute Post-Streptococcal Glomerulonephritis in Children: A Comprehensive Review. Curr Med Chem. 2022;29(34):5543-5559. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4899-1825-3_30"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36710"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13700"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36710"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-25T10:24:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-25T10:24:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6316"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51426"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medi